default&#xa0;defaultConclusiondefault37.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWomen’s and girl’s football has grown tremendously in the last 20 years and continues to grow. 
defaultThe FA launched its 5 year “Game 
defaultChanger” plan in 2012 to ensure that both the elite and the grassroots game can prosper in the coming years. 
default&#xa0;
default38.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe whole of the female pathway needs to be considered when examining sports policy. 
defaultIncreasing the physical literacy at an early age and ensurin
defaultg girls receive quality coaching focused to their needs at schools will hugely help to ensure that girls enjoy sport and have the opportunity to play if they want to. 
defaultThe current school clubs links programmes are vital to prevent drop off after school and 
defaultsupport should continue for these programmes, perhaps with additional funding for girls’ initiatives. 
default&#xa0;
default39.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFor grassroots football, ensuring that facilities are available and of suitable standard will be a challenge in the years to come as the ability to inve
defaultst in and maintain current facilities will come under further pressure. Meanwhile, while elite football is growing stronger, government can play a key role in encouraging media coverage which is so vital for attracting sponsorship to reinvest into the game
default. 
